title: ‘Planning and sophistication’ of Louvre heist suggests a ‘broader' network involved
description: Spiked online editor Tom Slater details the Louvre heist arrests and hints at a broader network involvement.  “These two individuals have been arrested,” Mr Slater told Sky News host Sharri Markson.  “The fact that the police are particularly touchy about information getting out there would suggest that a kind broader network beyond those two were involved in this heist.  “Maybe that indicates the level of planning and sophistication that goes beyond those two.”

title: ‘Cards stacked against’: Prince Andrew forced to leave his home
description: Writer and Broadcaster Esther Krakue explains the serious allegations Prince Andrew faces.  “This is probably as serious as it gets,” Ms Krakue told Sky News host Andrew Bolt.  “Stripping Prince Andrew of his titles is just the beginning.  “Now that the cards are stacked against him and things are looking dicier than usual … he has no choice but to leave.”

title: Queensland psychiatrist fights termination notice
description: Senior Child and Adolescent Psychiatrist Dr Jillian Spencer discusses her legal battle with Queensland Health after she was sent an employment termination notice by Queensland’s Children’s Hospital.   She has consistently spoken out about the potential harm of puberty blockers and gender affirming care when it comes to children.   Her termination notice, because of this pending legal action, has been put on hold.

title: ‘Fighting a war’: Iran allegedly orchestrates worldwide antisemitic attacks
description: Israel’s Deputy Foreign Minister Sharren Haskel explains revelations of Iran's alleged orchestration of worldwide antisemitic actions aimed at creating terror.  “Iran’s fighting a war, which in not a territorial war. It’s fighting a religious war, a cultural war where the Jews are at the frontline,” Ms Haskel told Sky News host Sharri Markson.   “Part of their strategy and how they're operating all around the world.”

title: Farmers uproar as government takes land without informing them
description: New South Wales farmer Anna Young shares concerns about the abrupt changes to transmission line routes affecting her properties without prior notification.  “They just said we’re moving the line,” Ms Young told Sky News host Paul Murray.   “They’ve studied this line … they’ve said multiple times that it’s not a good option.  “Some farmers haven’t actually been told yet.”

title: ‘Threat of China’: Albanese meets with Chinese Premier Li
description: Sky News host Sharri Markson discusses the “threat of China” as Prime Minister Anthony Albanese meets with Chinese Premier Li Qiang.  “The threat of China’s aggressive conduct is the underlying concern … two US aircraft have crashed over the South China Sea. This is alarming and we await more details from the United States about the cause,” Ms Markson said.  “Prime Minister Anthony Albanese met with Chinese Premier Li Qiang today for their bilateral, it was their seventh meeting and it came just a week after a dangerous incident for Australian pilots over the South China Sea.”

title: ‘Forced Acquisition’: Government takes farmland then complains when farmers are upset
description: New South Wales farmer Anna Young expresses frustrations over the lack of government transparency and consultation, particularly with structures which could severely impact her land.  “It’s going to be forced acquisition of our land,” Ms Young told Sky News host Paul Murray.   “Anyone in our position has a right to be upset about your land being taken.”

title: ‘A complete mess’: Transmission line planning continues after failing thresholds
description: Nationals MP Brendan Moylan explains the poor choices behind new transmission lines locations.  “It’s a complete mess,” Mr Moylan told Sky News host Paul Murray.  “This path that they’ve adopted failed five out of six of the government’s own thresholds.  “It just makes no sense.”

title: ‘Walking disaster’: Catherine Connolly won the Irish election off a ‘technicality’
description: Writer and Broadcaster Esther Krakue discusses Ireland’s recently elected hard-left President Catherine Connolly.  “She won basically off a technicality,” Ms Krakue told Sky News host Andrew Bolt.  “She is a complete walking disaster.  “She’s a typical champagne socialist.”

title: Trade truce between US and China looking likely
description: A trade truce between the United States and China looks likely ahead of the meeting between the country's leaders this week.   Donald Trump has arrived in Tokyo for talks with Japan's first female PM.  US Secretary of the Treasury Scott Bessent said the 100 per cent tariffs with China will be averted.

title: Hurricane Melissa strengthens to Category five storm
description: Hurricane Melissa has strengthened to a Category five storm as it begins lashing Jamaica.  Residents are preparing for what is expected to be the strongest Hurricane to ever hit the Island.  Forecasters expect the slow-moving system to drop as many as 40 inches of rain across parts of the island.

title: Donald Trump has not ruled out possibility of third term in office
description: US President Donald Trump has not ruled out the possibility of seeking a third term in office.  Mr Trump has conceded that he won’t be running as vice president.  Running as vice president would allow Donald Trump to circumvent the US Constitution and run for a third term.

title: ‘Completely failing’: Labor’s net-zero agenda deteriorating ‘on its own terms’
description: Nationals Senator Matt Canavan says Labor’s net-zero agenda is “completely failing”.  Mr Canavan told Sky News Australia that it’s “failing on its own terms”.  “Because they promised us that net zero would lower power prices.”

title: Labor preparing to scale back medal reform after veteran backlash
description: Labor is preparing to dramatically scale back plans to disqualify thousands of veterans from eligibility for retrospective honours.  A Senate Inquiry examining the bill is due to report back this week.  The bill remains highly contentious amongst veterans.

title: Mine explosion in NSW kills two people
description: A man and a woman have been killed in a mine explosion in the New South Wales far west.  Emergency services were called to the underground mine at Cobar in the early hours of this morning.  Another woman was rescued and airlifted to the hospital, suffering hearing damage and shock.  Authorities remain at the scene, and an investigation is underway.
